(23, 1, '2016-09-26 09:11:52', '2016-09-26 09:11:52', '<h2>How to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS</h2>\r\n<strong>Do you remember</strong> when you could run a fast WordPress website with just an Apache server and PHP? Yeah, those were the days! Things were a lot less complicated back then. <strong>Now, everything has to load lightning-fast!</strong> Visitors don’t have the same expectations about loading times as they used to. A slow website can have serious implications for you or your client.\r\n\r\nRelying on the latest technology is what will get you the most out of WordPress.\r\n<h2>WORDPRESS AWS SCALER</h2>\r\nThis is a how-to including scripts about how to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS with using Docker for deploying the WordPress core, RDS for the managed MySQL database server and CloudFront with S3 for delivering static files.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-requirements" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#requirements"></a>REQUIREMENTS</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Docker (installed on your development machine)</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS account</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS CLI see <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html</a></li>\r\n 	<li>WordPress AWS Scaler: <a href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler">https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine"></a>PREPARE AWS CLI ON DEVELOPER MACHINE</h2>\r\nInstall AWS CLI\r\n<pre><code>$ sudo pip install awscli\r\n</code></pre>\r\nConfigure AWS CLI\r\n<pre><code>$ aws configure\r\n</code></pre>\r\nCheck version of AWS CLI\r\n<pre><code>$ aws --version\r\n</code></pre>\r\nCheck if all works by listing existing ec2 instances\r\n<pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instances\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>CHECKOUT WORDPRESS AWS SCALER FROM GIT</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler.git</code>\r\n<code>$ cd wordpress-aws-scaler</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli"></a>USE THE WORDPRESS AWS SCALER CLI</h2>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-display-help" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#display-help"></a>DISPLAY HELP</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh --help</code></pre>\r\n<h2>LIST CURRENT SETTINGS AND SCAN AWS ACCOUNT FOR EXISTING WORDPRESS STACK</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh list\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account"></a>CREATE A NEW WORDPRESS STACK INTO YOUR AWS ACCOUNT</h2>\r\nExisting VPC, Security Groups, ELB, RDS, … will be re-used if they were created by this script. Otherwise they will be automatically created based on your settings: see “sh manage-wordpress.sh list”\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh create\r\n</code></pre>\r\nYou can run the create command over and over again – it won’t destroy anything. The script always checks what already exists and creates only what is missing.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs"></a>DELETE AN EXISTING WORDPRESS INCLUDING ALL AWS COMPONENTS AND ITS DATA -&gt; GO BACK TO ZERO RUNNING COSTS</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh delete\r\n</code></pre>\r\nUsually deleting the EC2 instances will take some seconds until they are really shut down. Until these instances still exist the script will not be able to delete the security group for security reasons from AWS side. If the security group is not yet deleted, wait for 2 min und re-run “sh manage-wordpress.sh delete”. When the EC2 instances are terminated, all components will be completely cleaned up. Zero costs!\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background"></a>THE FOLLOWING STEPS ARE NOT NEEDED FOR THE WORDPRESS AWS SCALER CLI SINCE THESE ARE AUTOMATICALLY DONE IN THE BACKGROUND.</h2>\r\n<h3><a id="user-content-how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry"></a>HOW TO BUILD THE WORDPRESS DOCKER IMAGE AND UPLOAD IT TO THE REGISTRY</h3>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress"></a>BUILD THE DOCKER IMAGE FOR WORDPRESS</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker build -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:0.2 .\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-check-that-our-docker-image-works" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#check-that-our-docker-image-works"></a>CHECK THAT OUR DOCKER IMAGE WORKS</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker run -p 80:80 -p 443:443 -it janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nVisit <a href="http://localhost/">http://localhost/</a>! Stop your server with <strong>Ctrl+C</strong>.\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-upload-docker-image-to-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#upload-docker-image-to-registry"></a>UPLOAD DOCKER IMAGE TO REGISTRY</h4>\r\n<pre><code id="user-content-setup-mysql-database-with-rds" class="anchor">$ docker push janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWant to run <strong>WordPress</strong> with <strong>Docker?</strong> Try <strong>Plesk Onyx</strong> <a href="https://www.plesk.com/onyx/">here</a>! Click <a href="https://www.plesk.com/">here</a> to learn more about Plesk.\r\n\r\nBe well, do good, and stay Plesky!', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-26 09:11:52', '2016-09-26 09:11:52', '', 17, 'http://local.wordpress.dev/2016/09/26/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(24, 1, '2016-09-26 09:12:39', '2016-09-26 09:12:39', '<strong>Do you remember</strong> when you could run a fast WordPress website with just an Apache server and PHP? Yeah, those were the days! Things were a lot less complicated back then. <strong>Now, everything has to load lightning-fast!</strong> Visitors don’t have the same expectations about loading times as they used to. A slow website can have serious implications for you or your client.\r\n\r\nRelying on the latest technology is what will get you the most out of WordPress.\r\n<h2>WORDPRESS AWS SCALER</h2>\r\nThis is a how-to including scripts about how to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS with using Docker for deploying the WordPress core, RDS for the managed MySQL database server and CloudFront with S3 for delivering static files.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-requirements" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#requirements"></a>REQUIREMENTS</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Docker (installed on your development machine)</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS account</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS CLI see <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html</a></li>\r\n 	<li>WordPress AWS Scaler: <a href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler">https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine"></a>PREPARE AWS CLI ON DEVELOPER MACHINE</h2>\r\nInstall AWS CLI\r\n<pre><code>$ sudo pip install awscli\r\n</code></pre>\r\nConfigure AWS CLI\r\n<pre><code>$ aws configure\r\n</code></pre>\r\nCheck version of AWS CLI\r\n<pre><code>$ aws --version\r\n</code></pre>\r\nCheck if all works by listing existing ec2 instances\r\n<pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instances\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>CHECKOUT WORDPRESS AWS SCALER FROM GIT</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler.git</code>\r\n<code>$ cd wordpress-aws-scaler</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli"></a>USE THE WORDPRESS AWS SCALER CLI</h2>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-display-help" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#display-help"></a>DISPLAY HELP</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh --help</code></pre>\r\n<h2>LIST CURRENT SETTINGS AND SCAN AWS ACCOUNT FOR EXISTING WORDPRESS STACK</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh list\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account"></a>CREATE A NEW WORDPRESS STACK INTO YOUR AWS ACCOUNT</h2>\r\nExisting VPC, Security Groups, ELB, RDS, … will be re-used if they were created by this script. Otherwise they will be automatically created based on your settings: see “sh manage-wordpress.sh list”\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh create\r\n</code></pre>\r\nYou can run the create command over and over again – it won’t destroy anything. The script always checks what already exists and creates only what is missing.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs"></a>DELETE AN EXISTING WORDPRESS INCLUDING ALL AWS COMPONENTS AND ITS DATA -&gt; GO BACK TO ZERO RUNNING COSTS</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh delete\r\n</code></pre>\r\nUsually deleting the EC2 instances will take some seconds until they are really shut down. Until these instances still exist the script will not be able to delete the security group for security reasons from AWS side. If the security group is not yet deleted, wait for 2 min und re-run “sh manage-wordpress.sh delete”. When the EC2 instances are terminated, all components will be completely cleaned up. Zero costs!\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background"></a>THE FOLLOWING STEPS ARE NOT NEEDED FOR THE WORDPRESS AWS SCALER CLI SINCE THESE ARE AUTOMATICALLY DONE IN THE BACKGROUND.</h2>\r\n<h3><a id="user-content-how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry"></a>HOW TO BUILD THE WORDPRESS DOCKER IMAGE AND UPLOAD IT TO THE REGISTRY</h3>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress"></a>BUILD THE DOCKER IMAGE FOR WORDPRESS</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker build -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:0.2 .\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-check-that-our-docker-image-works" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#check-that-our-docker-image-works"></a>CHECK THAT OUR DOCKER IMAGE WORKS</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker run -p 80:80 -p 443:443 -it janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nVisit <a href="http://localhost/">http://localhost/</a>! Stop your server with <strong>Ctrl+C</strong>.\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-upload-docker-image-to-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#upload-docker-image-to-registry"></a>UPLOAD DOCKER IMAGE TO REGISTRY</h4>\r\n<pre><code id="user-content-setup-mysql-database-with-rds" class="anchor">$ docker push janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWant to run <strong>WordPress</strong> with <strong>Docker?</strong> Try <strong>Plesk Onyx</strong> <a href="https://www.plesk.com/onyx/">here</a>! Click <a href="https://www.plesk.com/">here</a> to learn more about Plesk.\r\n\r\nBe well, do good, and stay Plesky!', 'How to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-26 09:12:39', '2016-09-26 09:12:39', '', 17, 'http://local.wordpress.dev/2016/09/26/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(25, 1, '2016-09-26 09:19:09', '2016-09-26 09:19:09', '<strong>Do you remember</strong> when you could run a fast WordPress website with just an Apache server and PHP? Yeah, those were the days! Things were a lot less complicated back then. <strong>Now, everything has to load lightning-fast!</strong> Visitors don’t have the same expectations about loading times as they used to. A slow website can have serious implications for you or your client.\r\n\r\nRelying on the latest technology is what will get you the most out of WordPress.\r\n<h2>WordPress AWS Scaler</h2>\r\nThis is a how-to including scripts about how to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS with using Docker for deploying the WordPress core, RDS for the managed MySQL database server and CloudFront with S3 for delivering static files.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-requirements" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#requirements"></a>Requirements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Docker (installed on your development machine)</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS account</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS CLI see <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html</a></li>\r\n 	<li>WordPress AWS Scaler: <a href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler">https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine"></a>Prepare AWS CLI on developer machine</h2>\r\n<strong>Install AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ sudo pip install awscli\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Configure AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws configure\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check version of AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws --version\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check if all works by listing existing ec2 instances</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instances\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Checkout WordPress AWS Scaler from GIT</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler.git</code>\r\n<code>$ cd wordpress-aws-scaler</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Use the WordPress AWS SCALER CLI display <a id="user-content-use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli">help</a></h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh --help</code></pre>\r\n<h2>List current settings and scan AWS account for existing WordPress stack</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh list\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account"></a>Create a new WordPress stack into your AWS account</h2>\r\nExisting VPC, Security Groups, ELB, RDS, … will be re-used if they were created by this script. Otherwise they will be automatically created based on your settings: see “sh manage-wordpress.sh list”\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh create\r\n</code></pre>\r\nYou can run the create command over and over again – it won’t destroy anything. The script always checks what already exists and creates only what is missing.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs"></a>Delete an existing WordPress installation including all AWS components and it''s data -&gt; go back to zero running costs</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh delete\r\n</code></pre>\r\nUsually deleting the EC2 instances will take some seconds until they are really shut down. Until these instances still exist the script will not be able to delete the security group for security reasons from AWS side. If the security group is not yet deleted, wait for 2 min und re-run “sh manage-wordpress.sh delete”. When the EC2 instances are terminated, all components will be completely cleaned up. Zero costs!\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background"></a>The following steps are not needed for the WordPress AWS Scaler CLI since these are automatically done in the background.</h2>\r\n<h3><a id="user-content-how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry"></a>How to build the WordPress Docker image and upload it to the registry</h3>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress"></a>Build the Docker image for WordPress</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker build -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:0.2 .\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-check-that-our-docker-image-works" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#check-that-our-docker-image-works"></a>Check that our docker image works</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker run -p 80:80 -p 443:443 -it janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nVisit <a href="http://localhost/">http://localhost/</a>! Stop your server with <strong>Ctrl+C</strong>.\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-upload-docker-image-to-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#upload-docker-image-to-registry"></a>Upload Docker image to registry</h4>\r\n<pre><code id="user-content-setup-mysql-database-with-rds" class="anchor">$ docker push janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWant to run <strong>WordPress</strong> with <strong>Docker?</strong> Try <strong>Plesk Onyx</strong> <a href="https://www.plesk.com/onyx/">here</a>! Click <a href="https://www.plesk.com/">here</a> to learn more about Plesk.\r\n\r\nBe well, do good, and stay Plesky!', 'How to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-26 09:19:09', '2016-09-26 09:19:09', '', 17, 'http://local.wordpress.dev/2016/09/26/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(26, 1, '2016-09-26 09:19:30', '2016-09-26 09:19:30', '<img class="alignnone wp-image-22 size-large" src="http://local.wordpress.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aws-1-1024x649.jpg" alt="aws-1" width="730" height="463" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Do you remember</strong> when you could run a fast WordPress website with just an Apache server and PHP? Yeah, those were the days! Things were a lot less complicated back then. <strong>Now, everything has to load lightning-fast!</strong> Visitors don’t have the same expectations about loading times as they used to. A slow website can have serious implications for you or your client.\r\n\r\nRelying on the latest technology is what will get you the most out of WordPress.\r\n<h2>WordPress AWS Scaler</h2>\r\nThis is a how-to including scripts about how to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS with using Docker for deploying the WordPress core, RDS for the managed MySQL database server and CloudFront with S3 for delivering static files.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-requirements" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#requirements"></a>Requirements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Docker (installed on your development machine)</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS account</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS CLI see <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html</a></li>\r\n 	<li>WordPress AWS Scaler: <a href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler">https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine"></a>Prepare AWS CLI on developer machine</h2>\r\n<strong>Install AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ sudo pip install awscli\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Configure AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws configure\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check version of AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws --version\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check if all works by listing existing ec2 instances</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instances\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Checkout WordPress AWS Scaler from GIT</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler.git</code>\r\n<code>$ cd wordpress-aws-scaler</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Use the WordPress AWS SCALER CLI display <a id="user-content-use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli">help</a></h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh --help</code></pre>\r\n<h2>List current settings and scan AWS account for existing WordPress stack</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh list\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account"></a>Create a new WordPress stack into your AWS account</h2>\r\nExisting VPC, Security Groups, ELB, RDS, … will be re-used if they were created by this script. Otherwise they will be automatically created based on your settings: see “sh manage-wordpress.sh list”\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh create\r\n</code></pre>\r\nYou can run the create command over and over again – it won’t destroy anything. The script always checks what already exists and creates only what is missing.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs"></a>Delete an existing WordPress installation including all AWS components and it''s data -&gt; go back to zero running costs</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh delete\r\n</code></pre>\r\nUsually deleting the EC2 instances will take some seconds until they are really shut down. Until these instances still exist the script will not be able to delete the security group for security reasons from AWS side. If the security group is not yet deleted, wait for 2 min und re-run “sh manage-wordpress.sh delete”. When the EC2 instances are terminated, all components will be completely cleaned up. Zero costs!\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background"></a>The following steps are not needed for the WordPress AWS Scaler CLI since these are automatically done in the background.</h2>\r\n<h3><a id="user-content-how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry"></a>How to build the WordPress Docker image and upload it to the registry</h3>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress"></a>Build the Docker image for WordPress</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker build -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:0.2 .\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-check-that-our-docker-image-works" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#check-that-our-docker-image-works"></a>Check that our docker image works</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker run -p 80:80 -p 443:443 -it janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nVisit <a href="http://localhost/">http://localhost/</a>! Stop your server with <strong>Ctrl+C</strong>.\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-upload-docker-image-to-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#upload-docker-image-to-registry"></a>Upload Docker image to registry</h4>\r\n<pre><code id="user-content-setup-mysql-database-with-rds" class="anchor">$ docker push janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWant to run <strong>WordPress</strong> with <strong>Docker?</strong> Try <strong>Plesk Onyx</strong> <a href="https://www.plesk.com/onyx/">here</a>! Click <a href="https://www.plesk.com/">here</a> to learn more about Plesk.\r\n\r\nBe well, do good, and stay Plesky!', 'How to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-26 09:19:30', '2016-09-26 09:19:30', '', 17, 'http://local.wordpress.dev/2016/09/26/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(27, 1, '2016-09-26 09:19:49', '2016-09-26 09:19:49', '<img class="alignnone wp-image-22 size-full" src="http://local.wordpress.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aws-1.jpg" alt="aws-1" width="1068" height="677" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Do you remember</strong> when you could run a fast WordPress website with just an Apache server and PHP? Yeah, those were the days! Things were a lot less complicated back then. <strong>Now, everything has to load lightning-fast!</strong> Visitors don’t have the same expectations about loading times as they used to. A slow website can have serious implications for you or your client.\r\n\r\nRelying on the latest technology is what will get you the most out of WordPress.\r\n<h2>WordPress AWS Scaler</h2>\r\nThis is a how-to including scripts about how to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS with using Docker for deploying the WordPress core, RDS for the managed MySQL database server and CloudFront with S3 for delivering static files.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-requirements" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#requirements"></a>Requirements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Docker (installed on your development machine)</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS account</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS CLI see <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html</a></li>\r\n 	<li>WordPress AWS Scaler: <a href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler">https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine"></a>Prepare AWS CLI on developer machine</h2>\r\n<strong>Install AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ sudo pip install awscli\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Configure AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws configure\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check version of AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws --version\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check if all works by listing existing ec2 instances</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instances\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Checkout WordPress AWS Scaler from GIT</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler.git</code>\r\n<code>$ cd wordpress-aws-scaler</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Use the WordPress AWS SCALER CLI display <a id="user-content-use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#use-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli">help</a></h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh --help</code></pre>\r\n<h2>List current settings and scan AWS account for existing WordPress stack</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh list\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account"></a>Create a new WordPress stack into your AWS account</h2>\r\nExisting VPC, Security Groups, ELB, RDS, … will be re-used if they were created by this script. Otherwise they will be automatically created based on your settings: see “sh manage-wordpress.sh list”\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh create\r\n</code></pre>\r\nYou can run the create command over and over again – it won’t destroy anything. The script always checks what already exists and creates only what is missing.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs"></a>Delete an existing WordPress installation including all AWS components and it''s data -&gt; go back to zero running costs</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh delete\r\n</code></pre>\r\nUsually deleting the EC2 instances will take some seconds until they are really shut down. Until these instances still exist the script will not be able to delete the security group for security reasons from AWS side. If the security group is not yet deleted, wait for 2 min und re-run “sh manage-wordpress.sh delete”. When the EC2 instances are terminated, all components will be completely cleaned up. Zero costs!\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background"></a>The following steps are not needed for the WordPress AWS Scaler CLI since these are automatically done in the background.</h2>\r\n<h3><a id="user-content-how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry"></a>How to build the WordPress Docker image and upload it to the registry</h3>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress"></a>Build the Docker image for WordPress</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker build -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:0.2 .\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-check-that-our-docker-image-works" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#check-that-our-docker-image-works"></a>Check that our docker image works</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker run -p 80:80 -p 443:443 -it janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nVisit <a href="http://localhost/">http://localhost/</a>! Stop your server with <strong>Ctrl+C</strong>.\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-upload-docker-image-to-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#upload-docker-image-to-registry"></a>Upload Docker image to registry</h4>\r\n<pre><code id="user-content-setup-mysql-database-with-rds" class="anchor">$ docker push janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWant to run <strong>WordPress</strong> with <strong>Docker?</strong> Try <strong>Plesk Onyx</strong> <a href="https://www.plesk.com/onyx/">here</a>! Click <a href="https://www.plesk.com/">here</a> to learn more about Plesk.\r\n\r\nBe well, do good, and stay Plesky!', 'How to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-26 09:19:49', '2016-09-26 09:19:49', '', 17, 'http://local.wordpress.dev/2016/09/26/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(28, 1, '2016-09-26 09:20:13', '2016-09-26 09:20:13', '<img class="alignnone wp-image-22 size-full" src="http://local.wordpress.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aws-1.jpg" alt="aws-1" width="1068" height="677" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Do you remember</strong> when you could run a fast WordPress website with just an Apache server and PHP? Yeah, those were the days! Things were a lot less complicated back then. <strong>Now, everything has to load lightning-fast!</strong> Visitors don’t have the same expectations about loading times as they used to. A slow website can have serious implications for you or your client.\r\n\r\nRelying on the latest technology is what will get you the most out of WordPress.\r\n<h2>WordPress AWS Scaler</h2>\r\nThis is a how-to including scripts about how to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS with using Docker for deploying the WordPress core, RDS for the managed MySQL database server and CloudFront with S3 for delivering static files.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-requirements" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#requirements"></a>Requirements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Docker (installed on your development machine)</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS account</li>\r\n 	<li>AWS CLI see <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/installing.html</a></li>\r\n 	<li>WordPress AWS Scaler: <a href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler">https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#prepare-aws-cli-on-developer-machine"></a>Prepare AWS CLI on developer machine</h2>\r\n<strong>Install AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ sudo pip install awscli\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Configure AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws configure\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check version of AWS CLI</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws --version\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<strong>Check if all works by listing existing ec2 instances</strong>\r\n<pre><code>$ aws ec2 describe-instances\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Checkout WordPress AWS Scaler from GIT</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler.git</code>\r\n<code>$ cd wordpress-aws-scaler</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Use the WordPress AWS SCALER CLI display help</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh --help</code></pre>\r\n<h2>List current settings and scan AWS account for existing WordPress stack</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh list\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#create-a-new-wordpress-stack-into-your-aws-account"></a>Create a new WordPress stack into your AWS account</h2>\r\nExisting VPC, Security Groups, ELB, RDS, … will be re-used if they were created by this script. Otherwise they will be automatically created based on your settings: see “sh manage-wordpress.sh list”\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh create\r\n</code></pre>\r\nYou can run the create command over and over again – it won’t destroy anything. The script always checks what already exists and creates only what is missing.\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#delete-an-existing-wordpress-including-all-aws-components-and-its-data---go-back-to-zero-running-costs"></a>Delete an existing WordPress installation including all AWS components and it''s data -&gt; go back to zero running costs</h2>\r\n<pre><code>$ sh manage-wordpress.sh delete\r\n</code></pre>\r\nUsually deleting the EC2 instances will take some seconds until they are really shut down. Until these instances still exist the script will not be able to delete the security group for security reasons from AWS side. If the security group is not yet deleted, wait for 2 min und re-run “sh manage-wordpress.sh delete”. When the EC2 instances are terminated, all components will be completely cleaned up. Zero costs!\r\n<h2><a id="user-content-the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#the-following-steps-are-not-needed-for-the-wordpress-aws-scaler-cli-since-these-are-automatically-done-in-the-background"></a>The following steps are not needed for the WordPress AWS Scaler CLI since these are automatically done in the background.</h2>\r\n<h3><a id="user-content-how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#how-to-build-the-wordpress-docker-image-and-upload-it-to-the-registry"></a>How to build the WordPress Docker image and upload it to the registry</h3>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#build-the-docker-image-for-wordpress"></a>Build the Docker image for WordPress</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker build -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest -t janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:0.2 .\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-check-that-our-docker-image-works" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#check-that-our-docker-image-works"></a>Check that our docker image works</h4>\r\n<pre><code>$ docker run -p 80:80 -p 443:443 -it janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nVisit <a href="http://localhost/">http://localhost/</a>! Stop your server with <strong>Ctrl+C</strong>.\r\n<h4><a id="user-content-upload-docker-image-to-registry" class="anchor" href="https://github.com/plesk/wordpress-aws-scaler/blob/master/README.md#upload-docker-image-to-registry"></a>Upload Docker image to registry</h4>\r\n<pre><code id="user-content-setup-mysql-database-with-rds" class="anchor">$ docker push janloeffler/wordpress-aws-scaler:latest\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWant to run <strong>WordPress</strong> with <strong>Docker?</strong> Try <strong>Plesk Onyx</strong> <a href="https://www.plesk.com/onyx/">here</a>! Click <a href="https://www.plesk.com/">here</a> to learn more about Plesk.\r\n\r\nBe well, do good, and stay Plesky!', 'How to auto-scale WordPress across multiple EC2 instances on AWS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-26 09:20:13', '2016-09-26 09:20:13', '', 17, 'http://local.wordpress.dev/2016/09/26/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
